<div class="modal fade" id="adminHelp" role="dialog" tabindex=0>
  <div class="modal-dialog">
    <div class="modal-content">
      <div class="modal-header">
        <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="close">&times;</button>
        <h4 class="modal-title">RAD Admin Help</h4>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-body">
        <h3>Power Searches</h3>
          <h4>Find Entries with Blank Fields (<span class="bi bi-dash-circle-fill"></span>)</h4>
            <p>Click the minus-sign button next to <strong>Search</strong> to find references that are missing at least one of: author, title, reference, source, page, abstract, or date. To restrict the search to a single field, use the dropdown caret next to the button and pick a field.</p>
            <p>The button writes the corresponding Solr query into the search box, so you can refine it further or share the resulting URL with another editor.</p>
          <h4>Find Entries with Problematic Characters (<span class="bi bi-question-circle-fill"></span>)</h4>
            <p>Click the question-mark button to find references whose author, title, reference, source, page, or abstract field contains an unusual character that may interfere with searching, exporting, or rendering. Use the dropdown caret to narrow to a single category:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Control / non-printing</strong> &mdash; ASCII control characters (excluding tab, line feed, carriage return), DEL, and the Unicode replacement character (U+FFFD), which usually indicates the value was decoded from broken UTF-8.</li>
              <li><strong>Invisible / zero-width</strong> &mdash; non-breaking space, soft hyphen, zero-width space/joiner/non-joiner, line/paragraph separators, and the byte-order mark.</li>
              <li><strong>Smart punctuation</strong> &mdash; curly quotes, en dash, em dash, and ellipsis. These render fine but break literal-string searches typed with straight ASCII equivalents.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The search uses Solr's regex query syntax against indexed terms. Characters that the field's tokenizer treats as word boundaries (e.g. non-breaking space) may be missed.</p>
          <h4>Cross-Reference: Refs vs. Sources</h4>
            <p>Solr can't join across the references and sources cores in a single query, so these two buttons do the work in two steps: pull one side's full list, then build a Solr query that excludes those values from the other side.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>On the <strong>References</strong> page, the <span class="bi bi-arrow-up-right-circle-fill"></span> button finds refs whose <code>source</code> field doesn't match any source's <code>name</code>. The matches are the ones you'll want to either correct (typo in the ref) or follow up on by adding the missing source.</li>
              <li>On the <strong>Sources</strong> page, the <span class="bi bi-arrow-up-left-circle-fill"></span> button finds sources that no reference points to. Useful for pruning dead entries.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Both buttons fill the search box with the generated Solr query so you can refine it or share the URL. Note that they degrade once the source list passes Solr's default boolean-clause limit (~1024 entries); if that ceiling is reached, queries will start failing and the underlying approach needs to change.</p>
        <h3>Automatic Input Cleanup</h3>
          <p>When you save a new or edited reference, the server normalises common copy-paste artefacts before storing the record. This keeps the database consistent so that literal-string searches reliably match what you see on screen. Specifically:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Curly quotes (<code>&ldquo; &rdquo; &lsquo; &rsquo;</code>) become straight quotes (<code>" "</code> and <code>'</code>).</li>
            <li>En dash and em dash (<code>&ndash; &mdash;</code>) become a hyphen (<code>-</code>).</li>
            <li>Ellipsis (<code>&hellip;</code>) becomes three dots (<code>...</code>).</li>
            <li>Non-breaking space and other exotic spaces become a regular space.</li>
            <li>Control characters, zero-width characters, soft hyphens, byte-order marks, and the Unicode replacement character are removed entirely.</li>
            <li>Tabs and line breaks in the abstract are preserved.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>If you need a character that would otherwise be normalised to remain in the saved record, you'll need to insert it directly in Solr; the admin form will always clean it.</p>
        <h3>Reference Editor</h3>
          <h4>Date Picker</h4>
            <p>The <strong>Date</strong> field uses ISO 8601 with three precision levels picked from the dropdown:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Year</strong> &mdash; just <code>YYYY</code> (e.g. <code>1932</code>). Use this when only the year is known.</li>
              <li><strong>Year-Month</strong> &mdash; <code>YYYY-MM</code> (e.g. <code>1932-04</code>). Use for monthly publications when the day isn't known or relevant.</li>
              <li><strong>Full Date</strong> &mdash; <code>YYYY-MM-DD</code> (e.g. <code>1932-04-15</code>).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The year drives the date-boost ranking on the public site, so even an approximate year helps relevance. Switching precision after typing clears the previous level's value &mdash; enter the new one in the now-visible field.</p>
            <p>Legacy entries occasionally have non-standard date strings (e.g. <code>"1977 ca."</code>) that don't fit any precision. When you open such a record, the picker shows the raw value in a text box with a <strong>Convert to standard date</strong> button. Saving without changing the value leaves it untouched (no validation error); pressing the button switches to the picker so you can enter a clean ISO date.</p>
          <h4>Publisher and Source</h4>
            <p>Most references only need a <strong>Publisher</strong> &mdash; the original publishing organization, which must match an existing entry in the sources directory (use the autocomplete suggestions, or click <strong>Create this publisher</strong> when you've checked it really doesn't exist).</p>
            <p>Tick <strong>Add separate source</strong> to reveal the <strong>Source</strong> field. Use this when a copy of the work can be obtained today from somewhere different from the original publisher &mdash; e.g. when the original publisher is defunct and an archive or reprint house now distributes the work. The Source must also match an existing sources entry. When the box is unticked, the Publisher is treated as both publisher and source.</p>
          <h4>Reference Type and Reviews</h4>
            <p>The <strong>Type</strong> dropdown categorises the work for the public-site filter (Technical Articles, Media, Reviews, Popular Articles). It's optional &mdash; leave it blank if no category fits.</p>
            <p>Selecting <strong>Reviews</strong> reveals a <strong>Reviewed work</strong> section with four extra fields: <strong>Reviewed Author</strong>, <strong>Reviewed Title</strong>, <strong>Reviewed Date</strong>, and <strong>Reviewed Source</strong>. These describe the work being reviewed (not the review itself, which goes in the normal Author/Title/Date fields). The Reviewed Source is free text &mdash; typically a URL &mdash; and is not validated against the sources directory. Switching the Type away from Reviews hides the section but preserves its values, so you can toggle back without losing input.</p>
          <h4>Save and Add Another</h4>
            <p>The <strong>Save and add another</strong> button on the new-reference modal saves the current entry and immediately blanks the per-record fields (Author, Title, Page, Abstract, and the Reviewed-work fields) so you can start typing the next reference. Fields that are usually shared across a batch &mdash; Date, Reference, Publisher, Source, and Type &mdash; are kept populated. This is useful when entering a series of articles from the same issue of a journal, or several reviews from the same reviewer.</p>
            <p>When you're done, dismiss the modal as normal. To force a full reset between entries, close and reopen the modal.</p>
        <h3>Campaigns</h3>
          <p>A campaign is a saved batch of references plus a description of what needs doing to them &mdash; e.g. "Replace en/em dashes in titles with hyphens; verify against printed copy." Use them when a clean-up task spans more references than you can finish in one session, or when work needs to be coordinated across editors.</p>
          <p>Create and rename campaigns on the <a href="/campaigns">Campaigns</a> page. From the references results, the <span class="bi bi-flag-fill"></span> <strong>Add to campaign</strong> action on each ref's overflow menu opens a picker so you can attach that ref to an existing campaign. Use the <span class="bi bi-list-task"></span> button in the results header to add every ref currently shown.</p>
          <p>Click <strong>Open in references</strong> on a campaign to load all of its refs into the search results &mdash; the URL gains a <code>?campaign=</code> parameter and a banner appears at the top of the page. While that banner is active, each ref's menu gains a <span class="bi bi-x-circle"></span> <strong>Remove from this campaign</strong> action. Solr URL-length limits cap a single batch at 100 refs; if a campaign has more, finish the visible batch and reopen the campaign to see the next.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-footer">
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-default" data-dismiss="modal">Close</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>